{"TopicId":217288,"ForumId":198,"TopicTitle":"Precision Control in KSP2 is limited compared to KSP1 (Digital vs Analog)","CreatedByName":"Anth","CreatedById":161238,"CreatedDateTime":"2023-05-21T01:10:22Z","PageNum":1,"Articles":[{"CreatedByName":"Anth","CreatedById":161238,"CreatedDateTime":"2023-05-21T01:10:22Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EKSP1 Version: \u003C/strong\u003E1.12.5.3190\u003Cbr\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EKSP2 Version: \u003C/strong\u003E0.1.2.0.22258\u003Cbr\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EOperating System: \u003C/strong\u003EWindows 10\u003Cbr\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003ECPU\u002BGPU\u002BRAM:\u003C/strong\u003E i9 9900K\u002B3070ti\u002B32GB\u003Cbr\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EMods Used: \u003C/strong\u003ENone\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EThree Sections for this one:\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003ESection 1: Shows how the Pitch/Yaw works via the indicators in KSP1 compared to KSP2\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsSpoiler\u0022 data-ipsspoiler=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsSpoiler_header\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cspan\u003ESpoiler\u003C/span\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsSpoiler_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EIn the following two videos:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003Cbr\u003E\nLook for what the Pitch/Yaw indicators are doing when there is normal control vs precision control.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EKSP1 bottom left of the screen:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003Cbr\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://youtu.be/pamiJyerPcI\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://youtu.be/pamiJyerPcI\u003C/a\u003E (16 Seconds)\u003Cbr\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003ESave File:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003Cbr\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://www.dropbox.com/s/7lwaskhlddi9y46/KSP1RWvsRCSPrecisionControl.sfs?dl=0\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://www.dropbox.com/s/7lwaskhlddi9y46/KSP1RWvsRCSPrecisionControl.sfs?dl=0\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EKSP2 on the Navball:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003Cbr\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://youtu.be/98HiyJkT92c\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://youtu.be/98HiyJkT92c\u003C/a\u003E (12 Seconds)\u003Cbr\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003ESave File:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003Cbr\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://www.dropbox.com/s/betijdle9ejrzuj/KSP2RWvsRCSPrecisionControl.zip?dl=0\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://www.dropbox.com/s/betijdle9ejrzuj/KSP2RWvsRCSPrecisionControl.zip?dl=0\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EWhat I noticed:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003Cbr\u003E\nNote how the KSP1 video shows that the Pitch/Yaw is analog. Also it can still get to their (non precision) maximums just in a dampened manner.\u003Cbr\u003E\nNote how the KSP2 video shows that the Pitch/Yaw is digital (off/on) and can\u0027t get to their maximums like KSP1.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nKSP1 in my opinion does this better.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003ESection 2: Shows how Reaction Wheels work in KSP1 vs KSP2\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsSpoiler\u0022 data-ipsspoiler=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsSpoiler_header\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cspan\u003ESpoiler\u003C/span\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsSpoiler_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EIn the following two videos:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003Cbr\u003E\nLook for a limited response in KSP2 verses KSP1\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EKSP1:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003Cbr\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://youtu.be/z5a0cETLGnQ\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://youtu.be/z5a0cETLGnQ\u003C/a\u003E (22 Seconds)\u003Cbr\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003ESave File:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003Cbr\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://www.dropbox.com/s/v0ajl7q8frpetg5/KSP1RWTestSave.sfs?dl=0\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://www.dropbox.com/s/v0ajl7q8frpetg5/KSP1RWTestSave.sfs?dl=0\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EKSP2:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003Cbr\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://youtu.be/jByHOLhCyzI\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://youtu.be/jByHOLhCyzI\u003C/a\u003E (25 Seconds)\u003Cbr\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003ESave File:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003Cbr\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://www.dropbox.com/s/jy1mkpol21t7agv/0120RWTestSave.zip?dl=0\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://www.dropbox.com/s/jy1mkpol21t7agv/0120RWTestSave.zip?dl=0\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThe digital (off/on) way that KSP2 does this is what is limiting the reaction wheels from Section 1.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003ESection 3: KSP2 vs KSP1 \u003Cabbr title=\u0022Reaction Control System\u0022\u003E\u003Cabbr title=\u0022Reaction Control System\u0022\u003ERCS\u003C/abbr\u003E\u003C/abbr\u003E under Precision Control which is actually pretty good.\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsSpoiler\u0022 data-ipsspoiler=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsSpoiler_header\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cspan\u003ESpoiler\u003C/span\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsSpoiler_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nHow KSP2 Does it:\u003Cbr\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://youtu.be/9aq_cabcPRo\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://youtu.be/9aq_cabcPRo\u003C/a\u003E (12 Seconds)\u003Cbr\u003E\nSave File:\u003Cbr\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://www.dropbox.com/s/6uja9neu35n6t1s/0120RCSPrecisionModeTest.zip?dl=0\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://www.dropbox.com/s/6uja9neu35n6t1s/0120RCSPrecisionModeTest.zip?dl=0\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nHow KSP1 Does it:\u003Cbr\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://youtu.be/ftGuQpM9vRs\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://youtu.be/ftGuQpM9vRs\u003C/a\u003E (15 Seconds)\u003Cbr\u003E\nSave File:\u003Cbr\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://www.dropbox.com/s/v0ajl7q8frpetg5/KSP1RWTestSave.sfs?dl=0\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://www.dropbox.com/s/v0ajl7q8frpetg5/KSP1RWTestSave.sfs?dl=0\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cabbr title=\u0022Reaction Control System\u0022\u003E\u003Cabbr title=\u0022Reaction Control System\u0022\u003ERCS\u003C/abbr\u003E\u003C/abbr\u003E Precision control is a bit different:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003Cbr\u003E\nKSP1 \u003Cabbr title=\u0022Reaction Control System\u0022\u003E\u003Cabbr title=\u0022Reaction Control System\u0022\u003ERCS\u003C/abbr\u003E\u003C/abbr\u003E is limited. Which I would never want to change.\u003Cbr\u003E\nKSP2 \u003Cabbr title=\u0022Reaction Control System\u0022\u003E\u003Cabbr title=\u0022Reaction Control System\u0022\u003ERCS\u003C/abbr\u003E\u003C/abbr\u003E works similar to KSP1 which is good.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nWell good when the \u003Cabbr title=\u0022Reaction Control System\u0022\u003E\u003Cabbr title=\u0022Reaction Control System\u0022\u003ERCS\u003C/abbr\u003E\u003C/abbr\u003E directional issues are addressed:\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Ciframe allowfullscreen=\u0022\u0022 data-controller=\u0022core.front.core.autosizeiframe\u0022 data-embedauthorid=\u0022161238\u0022 data-embedcontent=\u0022\u0022 data-embedid=\u0022embed2886615562\u0022 scrolling=\u0022no\u0022 src=\u0022https://forum.kerbalspaceprogram.com/index.php?/topic/217292-0120-the-vr-n1er-rcs-thrusters-dont-work-on-certain-keys-when-in-precision-mode/\u0026amp;do=embed\u0022 style=\u0022height:194px;max-width:502px;\u0022\u003E\u003C/iframe\u003E\u003Ciframe allowfullscreen=\u0022\u0022 data-controller=\u0022core.front.core.autosizeiframe\u0022 data-embedauthorid=\u0022161238\u0022 data-embedcontent=\u0022\u0022 data-embedid=\u0022embed8216907449\u0022 scrolling=\u0022no\u0022 src=\u0022https://forum.kerbalspaceprogram.com/index.php?/topic/217293-0120-rv-105-rcs-thrusters-do-not-work-at-all-when-precision-mode-is-on/\u0026amp;do=embed\u0022 style=\u0022height:194px;max-width:502px;\u0022\u003E\u003C/iframe\u003E\u003Ciframe allowfullscreen=\u0022\u0022 data-controller=\u0022core.front.core.autosizeiframe\u0022 data-embedauthorid=\u0022161238\u0022 data-embedcontent=\u0022\u0022 data-embedid=\u0022embed3047287233\u0022 scrolling=\u0022no\u0022 src=\u0022https://forum.kerbalspaceprogram.com/index.php?/topic/217294-0120-the-place-anywhere-7-rcs-thrusters-dont-work-on-certain-keys-when-in-precision-mode/\u0026amp;do=embed\u0022 style=\u0022height:194px;max-width:502px;\u0022\u003E\u003C/iframe\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nConclusion:\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cul\u003E\n\u003Cli\u003E\nReaction Wheels need to still access their potential maximum Pitch/Yaw/Roll in a dampened way like KSP1 does it (Make it Analog).\n\u003C/li\u003E\n\u003Cli\u003E\n\u003Cabbr title=\u0022Reaction Control System\u0022\u003E\u003Cabbr title=\u0022Reaction Control System\u0022\u003ERCS\u003C/abbr\u003E\u003C/abbr\u003E just needs to stay the same or similar to what it is already other than input issues (3 bug reports I put in Section 3)\n\u003C/li\u003E\n\u003C/ul\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cbr\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222023-06-02T00:35:40Z\u0022 title=\u002206/02/2023 12:35  AM\u0022 data-short=\u00221 yr\u0022\u003EJune 2, 2023\u003C/time\u003E by Anth12\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"}]}